# William Forbes, 7th Lord Forbes

**William Forbes, 7th Lord Forbes** (1513–1593) was a prominent Scottish landowner whose life and career were deeply intertwined with the turbulent political and religious landscape of 16th-century Scotland. As a member of the influential [House of Forbes](/House_of_Forbes), he played a significant role in the shifting alliances and conflicts that defined the era, particularly during the reign of [Mary, Queen of Scots](/Mary,_Queen_of_Scots) and the subsequent regency periods. His actions and alliances reflect the complex dynamics of Scottish nobility, where loyalty to crown, faith, and family often collided.

## Early Life and Family Background

William Forbes was born in 1513, the son of **John, 6th [Lord Forbes](/Lord_Forbes)** and **Christian Lundie**, a union that positioned him within one of Scotland’s most powerful noble families. The Forbes family had long been a formidable force in the northeast of Scotland, with their seat at [Druminnor Castle](/Druminnor_Castle), a stronghold that would later become a focal point in William’s own familial disputes. His upbringing would have been steeped in the traditions of Scottish nobility, where land, loyalty, and military prowess were paramount.

The Forbes family’s influence extended beyond mere landholding; they were active participants in the political and military affairs of the kingdom. William’s father, the 6th Lord Forbes, had navigated the treacherous waters of Scottish politics, aligning with various factions as the country oscillated between alliances with England and France. This legacy of political maneuvering would shape William’s own approach to leadership, as he inherited not only titles and lands but also the expectations and rivalries that came with them.

## Political and Military Involvement

### Protestant Reformation and Early Alliances

William Forbes’ early political career was marked by his involvement in the [Scottish Reformation](/Scottish_Reformation), a period of profound religious and political upheaval. In **April 1560**, his eldest son, **John, Master of Forbes**, and his half-brother, **"Black" Arthur Forbes**, signed a **band**—a formal agreement—alongside other Scottish nobles in [Edinburgh](/Edinburgh). This document committed them to the Protestant cause and pledged cooperation with the English army, which had been dispatched to Scotland to expel French troops. The French presence in Scotland had been a contentious issue, particularly during the regency of [Mary of Guise](/Mary_of_Guise), who had sought French support to maintain control over Scotland. The band signed by the Forbes brothers was part of a broader movement to assert Protestant dominance and reduce foreign influence in Scottish affairs.

This alliance with England was not merely a religious statement but a strategic one. The Forbes family, like many Scottish nobles, recognized the shifting balance of power in Europe and the potential benefits of aligning with England, particularly under the reign of [Elizabeth I](/Elizabeth_I_of_England). However, such alliances were fraught with risk, as they often provoked retaliation from rival factions, particularly those loyal to the Catholic cause and the exiled [Mary, Queen of Scots](/Mary,_Queen_of_Scots).

### The Marian Civil War and Feuds with the Gordons

Despite his family’s initial support for the Protestant cause, William Forbes found himself navigating a complex web of loyalties during the [Marian Civil War](/Marian_Civil_War), a conflict that erupted following Mary, Queen of Scots’ abdication in 1567. The war pitted supporters of the deposed queen against those loyal to her infant son, [James VI](/James_VI_and_I), and the regency government led by the [Earl of Moray](/James_Stewart,_1st_Earl_of_Moray).

In **July 1568**, Forbes was present at [Largs](/Largs) alongside the [Earl of Argyll](/Archibald_Campbell,_5th_Earl_of_Argyll), where they signed a letter addressed to the [Duke of Alva](/Fernando_%C3%81lvarez_de_Toledo,_3rd_Duke_of_Alba), the Spanish governor of the Netherlands. The letter expressed concern over Mary’s treatment in England and requested that the Duke intercede with [Philip II of Spain](/Philip_II_of_Spain) to petition [Elizabeth I](/Elizabeth_I_of_England) on her behalf. The nobles also sought Spanish military intervention in Scotland to counter their political enemies. This apparent shift in allegiance—from supporting Protestant England to seeking Catholic Spanish aid—highlights the fluid and often contradictory nature of Scottish politics during this period. Nobles like Forbes were frequently compelled to balance their religious convictions with pragmatic political considerations, particularly when their own survival and influence were at stake.

Despite this overture to Spain, English diplomats continued to regard William Forbes as a friend to England. This duality underscores the precarious position of Scottish nobles, who often had to navigate competing interests to maintain their power. Forbes’ actions during this time were likely motivated by a desire to protect his family’s interests rather than a firm ideological commitment to either the Protestant or Catholic cause.

The complexities of Forbes’ alliances became even more apparent during the **Marian Civil War**, when he took a firm stance against the supporters of Mary, Queen of Scots. This decision placed him in direct opposition to the powerful [Earl of Huntly](/Earl_of_Huntly), leader of the [Gordon clan](/Clan_Gordon), who remained a staunch supporter of the deposed queen. The rivalry between the Forbes and Gordon families was long-standing, rooted in competition for land, influence, and power in northeastern Scotland. The conflict escalated in **October 1571**, when the Earl of Huntly dispatched troops against Forbes. In response, the regency government, which supported Forbes, sent **200 men** to aid him.

The feud reached a violent climax at the **[Battle of Tillieangus](/Battle_of_Tillieangus)**, where **"Black" Arthur Forbes**, William’s half-brother, was killed. The conflict did not end there; further hostilities erupted in [Aberdeen](/Aberdeen) at the **[Battle of Craibstone](/Battle_of_Craibstone)**. During this engagement, **John, Master of Forbes**, was captured and taken to [Huntly Castle](/Huntly_Castle), the stronghold of the Gordon family. The English ambassador, **[Henry Carey, 1st Baron Hunsdon](/Henry_Carey,_1st_Baron_Hunsdon)**, viewed these clashes as a "private quarrel" or feud between the Forbes and Gordons, a perspective that underscored the personal and familial dimensions of Scottish noble conflicts. However, such feuds were rarely isolated; they often had broader political implications, as alliances and rivalries among noble families could shift the balance of power within the kingdom.

### Later Conflicts and Political Maneuvering

The latter years of William Forbes’ life were marked by internal family strife and continued political maneuvering. In **1590**, his eldest son, **John, Master of Forbes**, was accused of a shocking act of filial disrespect and violence. It was alleged that John had **imprisoned his father in a chamber at [Druminnor Castle](/Druminnor_Castle)** and struck him on the head with the pommel of his sword. This accusation was brought before the **[Privy Council of Scotland](/Privy_Council_of_Scotland)** by William’s younger sons, **Robert Forbes**, the Commendator of [Monymusk](/House_of_Monymusk), and **James Forbes of Fechell**. The Master of Forbes vehemently denied the charges, but the Privy Council, taking the allegations seriously, ordered that **Druminnor Castle** be placed under the control of **William Forbes of [Tolquhoun](/Tolquhon_Castle)** and other trusted individuals until Lord Forbes could either appear in [Edinburgh](/Edinburgh) or provide further testimony.

The situation escalated in **May 1591**, when the Master of Forbes counter-accused his brothers of turning their father against him. He claimed that while Lord Forbes was ill in [Dundee](/Dundee), Robert and James had **raided and robbed Druminnor Castle**. The younger brothers, in turn, secured royal letters supporting their occupation of the castle, further complicating the familial dispute. These events illustrate the volatile nature of noble family dynamics in Scotland, where inheritance, power, and personal grievances often led to bitter and sometimes violent conflicts.

Despite these internal strife, William Forbes remained an active participant in broader political alliances. In **November 1591**, he formed an alliance with **[George Keith, 5th Earl Marischal](/George_Keith,_5th_Earl_Marischal)** and **[Francis Hay, 9th Earl of Erroll](/Francis_Hay,_9th_Earl_of_Erroll)**, among others, against the **[Earl of Huntly](/George_Gordon,_1st_Marquess_of_Huntly)**. This coalition was part of a wider effort to counter the growing influence of the Gordon family, who continued to pose a significant threat to Forbes’ interests. The rivalry between the Forbes and Gordons extended into civic affairs as well; in **1592**, Forbes and Huntly backed rival candidates for the position of **Provost of Aberdeen**, further illustrating the pervasive nature of their feud.

## Family and Legacy

William Forbes’ personal life was as complex as his political career. He married **Elizabeth Keith**, the heiress of **Inverugie**, a union that further solidified the Forbes family’s landholdings and influence in northeastern Scotland. Their marriage produced several children, many of whom played significant roles in Scottish history:

- **[John Forbes, 8th Lord Forbes](/John_Forbes,_8th_Lord_Forbes)** (1542–1606), initially known as the **Master of Forbes**, succeeded his father as the 8th Lord Forbes. He married twice: first to **Margaret Gordon**, daughter of **[George Gordon, 4th Earl of Huntly](/George_Gordon,_4th_Earl_of_Huntly)** and **[Elizabeth Keith](/Elizabeth_Gordon,_Countess_of_Huntly)**. This marriage was strategically important, as it temporarily eased tensions between the Forbes and Gordon families. Margaret was the mother of **John, Master of Forbes**, who would later become the **9th Lord Forbes**. John’s second marriage was to **Janet Seton**, daughter of **Walter Seton of Touch**, who bore **Arthur, 10th Lord Forbes**.

- **Robert Forbes of Monymusk**, who served as the **Commendator of Monymusk**, a position that granted him significant ecclesiastical influence. His involvement in the dispute over Druminnor Castle highlights his role as a key figure within the family.

- **James Forbes of Fechell**, another of William’s sons, who joined Robert in accusing their half-brother, the Master of Forbes, of mistreating their father.

- **Anne Forbes**, who married **[Sir John Seton of Barns](/John_Seton,_Lord_Barns)** in **1588**. The Seton family was another prominent noble house, and this marriage further extended the Forbes’ network of alliances.

- **Jean Forbes**, who married **[James Ogilvy, 5th Lord Airlie](/James_Ogilvy,_5th_Lord_Ogilvy_of_Airlie)**, linking the Forbes family to the powerful Ogilvy clan.

- **Christian Forbes**, who married **George Johnston of [Caskieben](/Caskieben)**. Their son, **[Arthur Johnston](/Arthur_Johnston_(poet))**, would go on to become a renowned poet, adding a cultural dimension to the Forbes’ legacy.

The Forbes family’s alliances through marriage were not merely personal but strategic, designed to strengthen their political position and secure their influence. However, these alliances did not always prevent conflict. In **July 1592**, **John, Master of Forbes**, sought to arrange a marriage between his son and a sister of the **[Earl of Gowrie](/William_Ruthven,_1st_Earl_of_Gowrie)**. This proposed union was opposed by the **Earl of Huntly**, who recognized that it would weaken his political standing by strengthening the Forbes’ ties to another powerful noble family.

The intricate web of marriages, alliances, and conflicts that defined William Forbes’ life extended into the next generation. In **February 1600**, **Arthur, Master of Forbes**, married **Jean Elphinstone** in a double wedding ceremony held in [Edinburgh](/Edinburgh). The event, celebrated at the **Mint in the Cowgate**, also saw the marriage of **Anna Elphinstone** to the **[Earl of Sutherland](/Earl_of_Sutherland)**. The occasion was marked by royal favor, as **[James VI](/James_VI_and_I)** presented both brides with **gold chains** and **gold garnishings for their hair**, a gesture that underscored the importance of these noble unions.

## Death and Succession

William Forbes, 7th Lord Forbes, died in **1593**, leaving behind a legacy shaped by political intrigue, familial strife, and the enduring power struggles of the Scottish nobility. He was succeeded by his eldest son, **[John Forbes, 8th Lord Forbes](/John_Forbes,_8th_Lord_Forbes)**, who continued to navigate the complex landscape of Scottish politics. The Forbes family would remain a significant force in Scotland for generations, their history reflecting the broader themes of loyalty, betrayal, and ambition that defined the Scottish aristocracy during the 16th and 17th centuries.